","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"People are buying more clothing than ever before in some countries, but it's not sustainable. Could a \"wellbeing wardrobe\" help?","summaryShort":"The key to a sustainable wardrobe","tag":["tag\u002Fsustainability","tag\u002Ffuture-planet","tag\u002Ffashion"],"textToSpeech":false,"creationDateTime":"2022-09-14T00:30:47.450535Z","entity":"article","guid":"1693cc8b-5995-4af1-9837-4532e1b2b89b","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220913-how-to-fix-unsustainable-fast-fashion","modifiedDateTime":"2022-09-14T08:37:03.609283Z","project":"wwverticals","slug":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220913-how-to-fix-unsustainable-fast-fashion","cacheLastUpdated":1665920680260},"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220823-how-auckland-worlds-most-spongy-city-tackles-floods":{"urn":"urn:pubpipe:wwverticals:article:future\u002Farticle\u002F20220823-how-auckland-worlds-most-spongy-city-tackles-floods","_id":"6305631d43d9f46da86e5aa7","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["future\u002Fauthor\u002Fkate-evans"],"bodyIntro":"Cities need to become more ‘spongy’. Auckland is leading the way.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ETangled mats of muddy vegetation line the footpaths of Underwood Park, a narrow stripe of green winding along a creek beneath the small volcanic cone of Ōwairaka (Mt Albert) in Auckland, New Zealand. In the water, clumps of sticks and the occasional plastic bag are marooned on protruding rocks and branches.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EA winter storm swept through the city overnight, dropping heavy rain, and Te Auaunga (Oakley Creek), one of the city&rsquo;s longest urban streams, has overflowed its banks.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\"But that&rsquo;s supposed to happen,\" says Julie Fairey, chair of the Puketāpapa local board, who is showing me around Underwood and the neighbouring Walmsley Park.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe connected parks are designed to collect excess stormwater, soak it up like a sponge, and slowly release it back into the creek. The debris left behind is evidence this \"\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fthespinoff.co.nz\u002Fsociety\u002F22-03-2022\u002Fsometimes-its-supposed-to-flood\"\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Esecret infrastructure\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\"\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is working, Fairey says. The two parks are flanked on both sides by public housing developments. \"This stuff is designed to flood so that the houses don&rsquo;t,\" she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"infographic","imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220823-how-auckland-worlds-most-spongy-city-tackles-floods-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The researchers calculated that 50% of Auckland’s surface was green or blue, even after excluding its harbours","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220823-how-auckland-worlds-most-spongy-city-tackles-floods-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIt wasn&rsquo;t always this way, Fairey tells me, as we watch a black shag drying its wings on a rock. Less than a decade ago, the waterway was a concrete-lined culvert that ran through seldom-visited muddy fields. When it flooded, water sloshed into the surrounding suburbs. It collected engine oil, sediment and rubbish and sucked this unhealthy mixture out into the city&rsquo;s famous harbour, rendering the beaches \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nzgeo.com\u002Fstories\u002Fno-swimming\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Eunsafe to swim\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut in 2016, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fourauckland.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz\u002Fnews\u002F2019\u002F07\u002Fauckland-mayor-thrilled-at-te-auaunga-transformation\u002F\"\u003Ework began to free Te Auaunga from rigid concrete\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fourauckland.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz\u002Fnews\u002F2019\u002F07\u002Fauckland-mayor-thrilled-at-te-auaunga-transformation\u002F\"\u003Erestore it\u003C\u002Fa\u003E to a more natural, meandering shape. Its banks are now lush with native vegetation like harakeke (flax) and tī kouka (cabbage trees), as well as reeds, ferns and other filtering wetland plants.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe changes have increased this part of the city&rsquo;s ability to absorb excess rainfall, an attribute sometimes called &ldquo;sponginess&rdquo;. Auckland was recently named the most spongy global city in a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.arup.com\u002Fperspectives\u002Fpublications\u002Fresearch\u002Fsection\u002Fglobal-sponge-cities-snapshot\"\u003Ereport\u003C\u002Fa\u003E by multinational architecture and design firm Arup, thanks to its geography, soil type, and urban design &ndash; but experts warn it may not lead the pack for long.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs climate change intensifies extreme weather events worldwide, what can other cities learn from Auckland's successes &ndash; and failures?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220823-how-auckland-worlds-most-spongy-city-tackles-floods-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0cvtlkc"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220823-how-auckland-worlds-most-spongy-city-tackles-floods-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-asia-china-59115753%20\"\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Egodfather of the \"sponge cities\" concept\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is Peking University landscape architecture professor Yu Kongjian, who almost drowned in a flooded river as a child, but managed to pull himself to safety by grabbing hold of the willow branches and reeds that fringed its banks. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.arup.com\u002Fperspectives\u002Fsponginess-and-why-it-matters\"\u003EIn 2013, as an urban designer, he proposed\u003C\u002Fa\u003E that cities use nature rather than concrete to slow down heavy rain &ndash; an idea now \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fartanddesign\u002F2018\u002Fmar\u002F21\u002Fturning-cities-into-sponges-how-chinese-ancient-wisdom-is-taking-on-climate-change\"\u003Ebeing implemented in cities across China\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and gaining attention around the world.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs the planet warms, intense rainfall and flash flooding \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.metoffice.gov.uk\u002Fabout-us\u002Fpress-office\u002Fnews\u002Fweather-and-climate\u002F2021\u002Ffuture-extreme-rainfall-more-extreme-than-first-thought\"\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Eis predicted to\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E significantly increase. The spongier a city is, the more resilient it will be in the face of those threats. \"As our climate gets more extreme, we've got to deal with increasing hazards,\" says Mark Fletcher, global water leader at Arup and co-author of the company&rsquo;s \"spongy city\" report.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFletcher and his colleagues found that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.arup.com\u002Fperspectives\u002Fpublications\u002Fresearch\u002Fsection\u002Fglobal-sponge-cities-snapshot\"\u003EAuckland was the spongiest of seven global cities\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, marginally outscoring &ndash; in order of sponginess &ndash; Nairobi, Singapore, Mumbai, New York City, Shanghai and London.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220823-how-auckland-worlds-most-spongy-city-tackles-floods-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"A city that sits low on the ranking like London, it just means you have to try a bit harder to build some sponginess in – Mark Fletcher","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220823-how-auckland-worlds-most-spongy-city-tackles-floods-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe team mapped the proportion of grey (concrete and buildings), green (vegetation) and blue (ponds and streams) in the seven cities using Geographic Information Systems (GIS) technology, satellite imagery and machine learning. It then combined these maps with information about soil types and runoff potential to figure out each city&rsquo;s natural absorbency.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ELow-lying, coastal Auckland is New Zealand&rsquo;s largest city, with a population of 1.4 million people and an annual average rainfall of 1210mm (48in) &ndash; slightly more than New York, and twice as much as \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.metoffice.gov.uk\u002Fresearch\u002Fclimate\u002Fmaps-and-data\u002Fuk-climate-averages\u002Fgcpsvg3nc\"\u003ELondon\u003C\u002Fa\u003E typically receives in a year.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe researchers calculated that 50% of Auckland&rsquo;s surface was green or blue, even after excluding its harbours (London had the least of the seven cities, with 31%). In an intense rainfall event &ndash; 50mm falling in 24 hours &ndash; they estimated that 35% of the water falling on Auckland would be absorbed into these spongy blue and green parts, leaving 65% that would have to be dealt with by engineered stormwater systems &ndash; or else overflow and flood.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;It's a measure of how that city was developed, and its core underlying natural morphology,&rdquo; says Fletcher.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EYou might also like:\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cul\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20220809-how-the-mediterranean-became-the-worlds-most-invaded-sea\"\u003EThe crab invading the Mediterranean Sea\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20220816-the-botswana-buses-tackling-human-elephant-conflict\"\u003EAll aboard Botswana's Elephant Express\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20220802-climate-change-the-promise-and-danger-of-scotlands-peat\"\u003EThe promise and danger of Scotland's bog\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fli\u003E\n\u003C\u002Ful\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENairobi came a close second, at 34% spongy. The Kenyan capital has even more green and blue areas than Auckland &ndash; mainly parks and urban backyards &ndash; but higher run-off potential due to its clay-dominant soils, which absorb less water than sand or gravel. In the lowest-ranked city, London, just 22% of the water in a similar rainfall event would be absorbed &ndash; a risk highlighted in real life in July 2021, when 47.8mm of rain \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.theguardian.com\u002Fuk-news\u002F2022\u002Ffeb\u002F20\u002Flondon-flooding-poses-significant-risk-unless-immediate-action-taken\"\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Efell in one hour\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, causing \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fuk-england-london-57816647\"\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Ewidespread flooding\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E of roads, homes and Tube stations.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EKathy Waghorn, an urban researcher at the Auckland University of Technology&rsquo;s School of Future Environments, is not surprised that her city was rated as relatively spongy. \"We've got low urban density, we still have a lot of single-level dwellings, we still have gardens,\" she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAuckland&rsquo;s geomorphology plays a role too, she says: the narrow strip of land enfolded in two huge harbours, the dozens of small dormant \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nzgeo.com\u002Fstories\u002Fthe-fire-beneath-us\u002F\"\u003E\u003Cspan\u003Evolcanoes\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E dotting the city, the streams running down their green sides, and beneath them, the legacy of their lava &ndash; basalt and scoria caves and sinkholes. \"The volcanic field has shaped some of that open space,\" Waghorn says. \"Even our stone is sort of spongy.\"\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220823-how-auckland-worlds-most-spongy-city-tackles-floods-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p0cvtktq"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"future\u002Farticle\u002F20220823-how-auckland-worlds-most-spongy-city-tackles-floods-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut Waghorn and other researchers are concerned that Auckland will not keep its crown for long.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EA bundle of long-term trends all point towards the city becoming significantly less absorbent, even as climate change \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz\u002Fplans-projects-policies-reports-bylaws\u002Four-plans-strategies\u002Ftopic-based-plans-strategies\u002Fenvironmental-plans-strategies\u002Faucklands-climate-plan\u002Fpreparing\u002FPages\u002Fauckland-climate-change-future.aspx\"\u003Eincreases the number of extreme rainfall events\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and the risk of flooding. (In Auckland, for every degree of global warming, the intensity of short-duration storms\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.aucklandcouncil.govt.nz\u002Fplans-projects-policies-reports-bylaws\u002Four-plans-strategies\u002Ftopic-based-plans-strategies\u002Fenvironmental-plans-strategies\u002Faucklands-climate-plan\u002Fpreparing\u002FPages\u002Fauckland-climate